equation_narrative.headline: Co-evolutionary signal drives E/Q competition in charged surface context
equation_narrative.story: Position 34 in ubiquitin sits in a charged, surface-exposed context with 31 co-evolving positions providing strong evolutionary signal. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with polar and charged residues, with the logit lens showing scattered support for hydrophobic residues (V peaks at 12% at L0) that gradually gives way to polar character. The perception-to-decision transition at L23-25 is marked by intense MLP activity: L23 pushes toward E (+4.01 total projection), while L24-25 see competing signals. The final decision crystallizes at L30 when E surges from 5% to 47%, driven by co-evolutionary attention heads and MLP neurons that strongly favor E over the close competitor Q (which holds 40% at the end).

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather context from 2 structural contacts and 31 co-evolving positions, building a representation consistent with charged surface residues. Early layers show scattered hydrophobic character in the logit lens (V at 12% at L0, declining through L17), but this reflects initial embedding geometry rather than prediction. Attention features at L9 (F9:5728, F9:1281) encode local sequence context around the KIQDK motif. By L18, features shift toward abstract structural encoding (F18:4071, F18:1860). The representation's character becomes increasingly polar through the mid-layers, with the logit lens showing mixed support for small polar residues (S, T) and aromatics (Y, F) between L10-L23, consistent with the model encoding a flexible, surface-exposed position.
perception_phase.context_character: Surface-exposed position in a charged local environment (flanked by K33, D32, K29) with strong co-evolutionary coupling to 31 positions. The representation by L23 is consistent with polar/charged residues, though not yet committed to a specific amino acid.
key_information_sources: Co-evolutionary signal: 31 coupled positions provide strong evolutionary constraint, read primarily through attention heads at L30-31
Structural contacts: 2 nearby residues within 8Å, minimal direct packing constraints
Local sequence: KIQDK motif establishes charged surface context, encoded in L9 attention features (F9:5728, F9:1281, F9:2619)
L18 attention features (F18:4071, F18:1860) encode abstract structural properties of surface-exposed positions

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between L24-L30. L23 MLP neurons strongly favor E (+4.01 total projection, led by N23:4257, N23:4095), but L24-25 see competing signals that temporarily favor hydrophobic residues (L peaks at 21% at L25). The decisive moment is L30, where co-evolutionary attention head H30:8 (+1.38 projection) and MLP neuron N30:3282 (+0.89 projection) drive E from 5% to 47%. L31-32 see continued E support through co-evolutionary head H31:17 (+3.22 projection), though Q remains a strong competitor throughout, holding 40% at the final layer.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from perception to decision. L23 MLP pushes strongly toward E (+4.01), but L24-25 attention heads act as erasers (-1.57 attention delta at L25), creating temporary uncertainty. AA-specific prediction features first appear at L24 (F24:9782, F24:9558), and by L30, high-enrichment prediction channels dominate (F30:7328, F30:6262).

candidates.narrative: E emerges as a serious contender at L23 when MLP neurons N23:4257 and N23:4095 provide strong support (+0.51 and +0.39 projections respectively). After temporary suppression at L24-29 (dropping to 5% at L29), E surges decisively at L30 through co-evolutionary attention head H30:8 (+1.38 projection) and MLP neuron N30:3282 (+0.89 projection toward E via strong D preference). L31-32 see massive co-evolutionary support through H31:17 (+3.22 projection) and MLP neurons N31:4793 and N32:1774 (+1.00 and +1.01 projections). E peaks at 92% at L32 before Q competition brings it to 59% final.
candidates.key_layers: Strong at L23, suppressed L24-29, surges at L30, peaks at L32
key_evidence: N23:4257 (MLP, +0.51 proj) — E/Q/P-voting neuron activates strongly
H30:8 (attn, +1.38 proj) — co-evolutionary head (62% coevol attention) writes E
H31:17 (attn, +3.22 proj) — strongest co-evolutionary writer (69% coevol attention)
N30:3282 (MLP, +0.89 proj) — votes D>I>W but projects strongly toward E
N32:1774 (MLP, +1.01 proj) — D/E-specific neuron with nearly equal support

candidates.narrative: Q maintains steady support throughout the decision phase, never dropping below 2.7% after L8. It receives consistent backing from MLP neurons that favor polar residues (N23:4257 votes Q at +0.53, N29:4471 votes Q at +0.48). Q's support comes from the same co-evolutionary and polar-context features that favor E, but with slightly lower magnitude. The E/Q competition remains close through L33, with Q holding 40% against E's 59%, reflecting the chemical similarity and functional interchangeability of these residues in this surface-exposed context.
candidates.key_layers: Steady presence L8-L33, peaks at 40% final
key_evidence: N23:4257 (MLP, +0.53 proj to Q) — same neuron that favors E also supports Q
N29:4471 (MLP, +0.48 proj to Q) — Q/E/D-voting neuron
F30:10062 (attn, 22.6 proj) — attention feature supporting polar residues
Maintains 40% final probability despite strong E push

candidates.narrative: V shows 12% probability at L0, the highest of any hydrophobic residue in the initial embedding, but this reflects the embedding space geometry rather than any model belief about this position. The representation at L0 has not yet incorporated structural or evolutionary context. V declines steadily through the perception phase (8% at L8, 2.8% at L17, 0.6% at L23) as the model reads the charged local sequence and surface-exposed structural context, which are incompatible with hydrophobic burial. By the decision phase, V is effectively eliminated (0.03% final).
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L0 (12%), eliminated by L23
key_evidence: L0 embedding geometry creates initial hydrophobic-leaning representation
Declines as charged context (K, D neighbors) is incorporated L1-L17
MLP erasers at L14 (N14:2390, -0.42 proj) suppress hydrophobic character

candidates.narrative: H briefly leads the logit lens at L2 (12.8%), reflecting early representation character consistent with charged/polar residues in the local KIQDK context. This is not a prediction but rather the model's initial encoding of the position's chemical environment. H receives support through mid-layers from neurons that favor charged residues (N19:4466 votes H at +0.31), but loses ground in the decision phase as the co-evolutionary signal more specifically constrains the choice to E/Q. H drops to 0.12% final as the model commits to the longer-chain acidic/amide pair.
candidates.key_layers: Leads at L2, declines through L8-L23, eliminated by L29
key_evidence: L2 logit lens peak (12.8%) reflects charged-residue representation character
N19:4466 (MLP, +0.31 proj to H) — charged-residue neuron
Suppressed by co-evolutionary signal favoring E/Q over H

candidates.narrative: D shows early support (peaks at 9% at L3) as the model encodes the acidic character of the local context, but loses decisively to E in the decision phase. The key distinction emerges at L30-32, where MLP neurons that vote for both D and E (N30:3282 votes D at +1.21, E at +0.89; N32:1774 votes D at +1.04, E at +1.01) ultimately project more strongly toward E. The co-evolutionary signal appears to favor the longer glutamate side chain over the shorter aspartate, and D drops to 0.53% final.
candidates.key_layers: Early support L3-L8, eliminated by L30
key_evidence: N30:3282 (MLP) votes D>E but context favors E interpretation
N32:1774 (MLP) votes D≈E with slight D preference
Co-evolutionary heads favor E over D in final layers

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from scattered hydrophobic/aromatic character to polar/charged character as structural and evolutionary context accumulates. The logit lens shows frequent lead changes between hydrophobic (L, V, A) and polar (S, Y, F) residues, but this reflects the model assembling a representation of a flexible surface position, not making predictions. MLP neurons at L14 (N14:2390, -0.42 total projection) strongly suppress hydrophobic character, while L15 neurons (N15:2143, +0.15 proj) begin to favor E specifically.

The perception-to-decision transition is turbulent. L23 MLP strongly favors E (+4.01 total projection, led by N23:934 at +0.57 and N23:4257 at +0.51), but L24-25 attention heads act as erasers (L25 attention delta -1.57), creating temporary uncertainty and allowing hydrophobic residues (L, T, F) to briefly lead the logit lens. This is the model's last reconsideration before commitment. AA-specific prediction features appear at L24 (F24:9782, F24:9558), marking the shift from context encoding to amino acid selection.

The decisive commitment to E occurs here. L30 co-evolutionary attention head H30:8 (+1.38 projection, 62% coevol attention) and MLP neuron N30:3282 (+0.89 projection) drive E from 5% to 47%. L31 sees the strongest single writing event in the entire forward pass: co-evolutionary head H31:17 (+3.22 projection, 69% coevol attention) massively reinforces E. L32 MLP neurons N32:1774 and N32:3621 (+1.01 and +0.87 projections) push E to its peak of 92%. However, L32 also sees strong suppression from N32:4433 (-1.72 projection favoring hydrophobic residues), allowing Q to recover to 40% final.

deep_dives.label: Co-evolutionary attention L30-31
deep_dives.caption: The decisive co-evolutionary signal arrives here. H30:8 and H31:17 read from the 31 coupled positions (69% and 62% coevol attention respectively) and write strongly toward E. These are the model's primary mechanism for incorporating evolutionary constraints.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision neurons L30-32
deep_dives.caption: The final decision is made here. L30 N30:3282 and L32 N32:1774 vote for D/E with strong projections toward E. L31 N31:4793 and N31:886 provide additional E support. L32 N32:4433 acts as a strong eraser (-1.72 proj), favoring hydrophobic residues and allowing Q to remain competitive.

deep_dives.label: Perception features L9-18
deep_dives.caption: L9 features encode the local KIQDK sequence context (F9:5728, F9:1281, F9:2619). L18 features shift to abstract structural properties (F18:4071, F18:1860), encoding surface exposure and flexibility. These build the representation that will constrain the decision phase.

deep_dives.label: Transition MLPs L23-24
deep_dives.caption: L23 strongly favors E (N23:934 +0.57, N23:4257 +0.51, +4.01 total), but L24 sees competing signals (N24:1819 -0.69 eraser, N24:2857 -0.43 eraser). This is where perception becomes decision, with the first AA-specific prediction neurons activating.

deep_dives.label: Decision features L30-33
deep_dives.caption: L30 features (F30:7328, F30:6262, F30:5602) are high-projection attention and MLP features supporting the E/Q decision. L33 features (F33:324, F33:3289, F33:2277) are the final prediction channels with very high projections (>95), representing the model's committed output.

deep_dives.label: Velocity spike L29-30
deep_dives.caption: L29 sees E suppression (-3.74 total MLP projection, led by N29:4973 at -1.07), but L30 reverses this dramatically (+1.69 total MLP projection). This is the moment of commitment, driven by co-evolutionary attention and D/E-voting MLP neurons.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts E by integrating strong co-evolutionary signal from 31 coupled positions with the local charged surface context (K33, D32, K29 neighbors). The decisive evidence comes at L30-31, where co-evolutionary attention heads H30:8 and H31:17 read evolutionary constraints and write toward E with combined +4.60 projection. MLP neurons at L30-32 that vote for acidic residues (N30:3282, N32:1774) reinforce this choice. Q remains competitive (40% final) because it shares the polar, charged-compatible character that the evolutionary and structural context demand, but E wins due to stronger support from co-evolutionary coupling and slightly better fit to the acidic local environment.
